  "summary": "Hercule Poirot and Captain Hastings discuss the unsettling anonymous letter signed \"ABC.\" While Hastings suggests the letter is merely a poorly executed prank by a drunkard, Poirot expresses deep unease, noting that his experience suggests something is wrong. Poirot admits that he would find a robbery on the twenty-first more comforting than a murder, as it would mean the letter's threat was not lethal. Meanwhile, on Thursday, June 20th, a tall man with a hunchbacked and squinting appearance named Alexander Bonaparte Caster sits in a shabby bedroom and marks a name on a printed list.\n\nOn the twenty-first, Inspector Japp of Scotland Yard visits Poirot and Hastings to report that the events predicted for the day were nothing more than minor disturbances: a broken store window and two people being drunk and disorderly. This news relieves Poirot, who admits he may have been mistaken in taking the letter so seriously. Japp dismisses such communications as common hoaxes written by people seeking a thrill. After Japp departs, Poirot and Hastings engage in lighthearted banter regarding Hastings' thinning hair. Poirot eventually reflects on his own heightened sensitivity, comparing his concern over the letter to a blind watchdog barking at nothing. He concludes by stating that if he were to choose a type of crime to investigate, he would choose murder.",
